972,http://www.armslist.com/posts/3695972,"For Sale:  Indirect Combat Relay Optic (ICRO) - ""Shoot Around Corner"" Optic","North County, San Diego, California",$ 250,"Listed On: Tuesday, November 11, 2014",Optics,no type,no type,no type,no type,"This is an Indirect Combat Relay Optic and was designed and built for the U.S. Military by a company called Exponent Inc.  for use by special forces units during  U.S. military operations in Iraq and Afghanistan.
It is not a very common item . The items is brand new and I only took it out of the box to take the pictures for this posting. This unit has never been mounted on a weapon.

The ICRO fits over the front of pretty much a Close Combat Optic (CCO) or M68 reflex sight and gives the user the ability to aim the CCO from a better protected position by allowing the weapon to be sighted 90 degrees off the barrel. In laymans terms, that means you can look around corners using this device. This device will also not affect the zero or boresight of the weapon. The ICRO uses a little mirror that flips in position on demand to enable you to look through the sight from the side of the weapon. The mirror also flips out of the way when not in use so that the sight can be used as normal. The ICRO is an elegantly simple solution to an age old problem.

Again, this item is brand new in the box and comes with the instruction sheet and one extra elastic band. This little thing is a great piece of equipment and an awesome addition to any soldier's toolbox, especially if you are getting ready to deploy to an urban combat environment where a shoot-around-the-corner device would give you an unparalleled advantage.

Selling price is $250, including shipping and insurance. This item can only be shipped in the USA, so no foreign orders please.  I prefer Paypal but will accept a money order but please no personal checks.
Pictures:
1) ICRO in box with user's manual
2) ICRO mounted on Aimpoint (not included)

3) 2 ICROS side-by-side for comparison purpose (showing ICRO in ""open"" position for normal use of your CCO, and in ""closed"" position to acquire targets at 90 degree angle looking through your CCO)."
